ijk","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","of North Hampton, Yorkshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1390–":"1390–Deceased","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1382–Female":"1382–Deceased","1385–1410":"1385–1410","1390–Male":"1390–Deceased","1395–Female":"1395–Deceased","1396–Female":"1396–Deceased","1410–Female":"1410–Deceased","1335–1390":"1335–1390","1339–Female":"1339–Deceased","1335":"1335","1410":"1410","Abt 1396":"about 1396","Abt 1359":"about 1359","1396":"1396","1385":"1385","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1339":"1339","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","South Cave, East Riding of Yorkshire, England":"South Cave, Yorkshire East Riding, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","of North Hampton, Yorkshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cave","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in East Yorkshire called Cave, apparently from a river name derived from Old English <i>cāf</i> ‘swift’.","English (of Norman origin): nickname from Norman and Picard Old French <i>cauf</i> (from Latin <i>calvus</i>) ‘bald’.","French: topographic name for someone who lived in or near a cave, from Old French <i>cave</i> ‘cave’, ‘cellar’ (from Latin <i>cavea</i>, a derivative of <i>cavus</i> ‘hollow’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Cavin","meanings":["Scottish (Wigtownshire): variant of <b>Caveen</b>, a shortened form of Manx <i>Mac Dhaimhín</i>, son of <i>Daimhín</i>. The personal name is a diminutive of Gaelic <i>damh</i> ‘bard, poet’.","French: diminutive of   Cave  ."]},{"name":"Caves","meanings":["English: variant of   Cave  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Keeve","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Cave  . This surname is rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Chaffee","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): descriptive nickname from a derivative of Old French <i>chauf</i> ‘bald’ (from Latin <i>calvus</i>). Compare   Cave  ."]},{"name":"Cavett","meanings":["Scottish (of French origin): altered form of French <b>Cavet</b>, which is either a diminutive of   Cave   3 or a metonymic occupational name for a laborer, one who used a <i>cavet</i>, an Old Occitan word for a tool for clearing ground for cultivation."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander Cave was born in 1390, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Alexander Cave, was 55 and his mother, Catherine de Grindell, was 52. He had at least 2 daughters with Constantina Leeds."},"et":{"1390–":"1390–Surnud","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1382–Female":"1382–Surnud","1385–1410":"1385–1410","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","1396–Female":"1396–Surnud","1410–Female":"1410–Surnud","1335–1390":"1335–1390","1339–Female":"1339–Surnud","1335":"1335","1410":"1410","Abt 1396":"umbes 1396","Abt 1359":"umbes 1359","1396":"1396","1385":"1385","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1339":"1339","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","South Cave, East Riding of Yorkshire, England":"South Cave, Yorkshire East Riding, In